window.MYTHOS = {"meta":{"title":"Mythos Daily","tagline":"A passage from Greek and Roman myth to begin the day.","note":"Daily lines are faithful editorial renderings after the cited primary source. Each entry names a public-domain edition where the original text can be read in full.","updated":"2026-06-13"},"entries":[{"id":"apollo-daphne","title":"Apollo and Daphne","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["desire","transformation","the limits of power"],"star":{"x":0.18,"y":0.3,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book I, lines 452–567","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain); also Perseus Digital Library."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"Spare me, father — let the earth swallow this shape that draws him on, or change the body whose beauty has undone me.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses I"},"summary":"Stung by Cupid's arrow, the god Apollo burns with love for the nymph Daphne, who has sworn herself to a virgin life like Diana. He pursues; she flees. At the river's edge, exhausted, she begs her father, the river-god Peneus, to destroy the beauty that has trapped her. He answers by turning her into a laurel tree — and Apollo, denied her, claims the laurel as his sacred emblem forever.","context":"Apollo and Daphne opens the long chain of love-and-transformation stories that give the Metamorphoses its shape. Ovid frames it as a contest of arrows: Apollo has just boasted of killing the serpent Python, and the small god Cupid punishes that arrogance by making the great archer helpless. It is the poem's thesis in miniature — even the gods are not exempt from change, and power over monsters is no power over the heart.","characters":[{"name":"Apollo","note":"God of the sun, prophecy, music, and the bow. Here he is humbled: the master archer felled by a smaller archer's arrow."},{"name":"Daphne","note":"A nymph, daughter of the river Peneus, devoted to the hunt and to chastity. Her name becomes the Greek word for laurel."},{"name":"Cupid","note":"Roman Eros, god of desire. He fires two arrows — gold to kindle love in Apollo, lead to repel it in Daphne."},{"name":"Peneus","note":"Daphne's father, a Thessalian river-god, who grants her plea by transforming her."}],"reception":"The chase became one of the most painted and sculpted scenes in Western art — above all Bernini's marble of 1625, which freezes the instant bark climbs Daphne's fingers into leaves. Poets from Petrarch to the Renaissance read the laurel (Latin laurus) as the prize of poetry itself, so that Apollo's loss is recast as the origin of the poet's crown. The myth has since been read as a story about consent and the costs of unwanted pursuit.","connections":[{"to":"narcissus-echo","why":"Another Ovidian love that ends in transformation rather than union."},{"to":"phaethon","why":"Apollo as the sun-god whose son will later beg to drive his chariot."}]},{"id":"narcissus-echo","title":"Narcissus and Echo","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["self-love","longing","the unanswered voice"],"star":{"x":0.34,"y":0.22,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book III, lines 339–510","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"Whoever you are, come out to me! — and the hills gave back only: come out to me.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses III"},"summary":"Echo, a nymph cursed to repeat only the last words she hears, falls hopelessly in love with the beautiful youth Narcissus and is spurned. She wastes away until only her voice remains. Narcissus, who has scorned every lover, is made to fall in love with his own reflection in a pool; unable to possess it, he too pines away and is changed into the flower that bears his name.","context":"Ovid braids two punishments into one scene: Echo, robbed of her own words, and Narcissus, trapped by his own image. The pairing is deliberate — one cannot speak first, the other cannot love anything but self. It belongs to the Theban book of the Metamorphoses, a sequence about seeing and being seen that climaxes in the doomed gaze.","characters":[{"name":"Narcissus","note":"A youth of fatal beauty, son of the river Cephisus. A seer had warned he would live long only if he never knew himself."},{"name":"Echo","note":"A talkative nymph silenced by Juno, left able only to echo others. Love leaves her a disembodied voice."},{"name":"Nemesis","note":"The goddess of retribution, who answers the prayers of Narcissus's rejected lovers."}],"reception":"The story gave its name to both a flower and, by way of Freud and Havelock Ellis, to narcissism as a psychological term. Echo became a figure for poetic repetition and for the woman denied her own voice; the pool and reflection recur from Caravaggio's painting to modern meditations on the image-saturated self. Few myths have proven so portable into the age of the screen.","connections":[{"to":"apollo-daphne","why":"Desire that destroys rather than unites — transformation as the only escape."},{"to":"pygmalion","why":"A counter-case: love directed at an image that, against the odds, comes alive."}]},{"id":"icarus-daedalus","title":"Daedalus and Icarus","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["ingenuity","limits","a father's grief"],"star":{"x":0.5,"y":0.16,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book VIII, lines 183–235","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"Keep to the middle way, my son: too low, the sea will weight your wings; too high, the sun will burn them.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses VIII"},"summary":"Imprisoned on Crete, the master craftsman Daedalus builds wings of feathers and wax so he and his son Icarus can escape by air. He warns the boy to fly a middle course. Exhilarated, Icarus climbs toward the sun; the wax melts, the feathers scatter, and he falls into the sea that now bears his name, while his father can only cry out his lost name.","context":"The flight follows Daedalus's earlier ingenuity — the labyrinth he built to hold the Minotaur. Ovid turns the craftsman's triumph into a tragedy of overreach, but pointedly locates the fatal error in youthful joy rather than malice. The 'middle way' is among antiquity's clearest images of moderation, and of the price of ignoring it.","characters":[{"name":"Daedalus","note":"The archetypal inventor and craftsman, builder of the Labyrinth. His genius frees him and kills his son."},{"name":"Icarus","note":"His son, undone not by cunning but by the simple thrill of height."},{"name":"Minos","note":"King of Crete, who imprisoned them — the constraint the wings were built to defeat."}],"reception":"Bruegel's painting famously hides the falling boy in a corner while a ploughman works on, an image W.H. Auden read as the world's indifference to private catastrophe. The myth anchors modern debates about technology and hubris, and 'flying too close to the sun' has passed into ordinary speech. Daedalus also lent his name to the artist-figure of Joyce's fiction.","connections":[{"to":"theseus-minotaur","why":"Daedalus built the Labyrinth that Theseus must later escape."},{"to":"phaethon","why":"Another young son destroyed by reaching too near the sun."}]},{"id":"orpheus-eurydice","title":"Orpheus and Eurydice","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["grief","art against death","the backward glance"],"star":{"x":0.64,"y":0.28,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book X, lines 1–85","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain); cf. Virgil, Georgics IV."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"He had almost reached the upper air when fear turned him — he looked, and she slipped back, twice lost.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses X"},"summary":"When his bride Eurydice dies of a snakebite, the musician Orpheus descends to the underworld and so moves its rulers with his song that they release her — on one condition: he must not look back until both have reached the light. At the threshold, anxious, he turns. She fades into the dark a second time, and he is left to mourn until his own death.","context":"Ovid tells the story as the opening of his tenth book, where it becomes the frame for a chain of songs Orpheus himself sings. Virgil had given an earlier, fuller version in the Georgics. The single forbidden glance is the hinge of the whole myth: art can almost defeat death, but the artist's human doubt undoes the bargain at the last step.","characters":[{"name":"Orpheus","note":"Legendary poet and musician whose song could move stones, beasts, and the dead. Son of a Muse."},{"name":"Eurydice","note":"His bride, lost to a snakebite, then lost again to a backward glance."},{"name":"Hades and Persephone","note":"Rulers of the underworld, persuaded — uniquely — to grant a soul's return."}],"reception":"The descent inspired the first operas — Monteverdi's Orfeo (1607) and later Gluck — making it foundational to the form. Rilke's Sonnets to Orpheus and films from Cocteau to Black Orpheus keep reworking it, and it remains the central myth of the artist who bargains with loss. The backward glance is one of literature's most reused gestures.","connections":[{"to":"persephone-demeter","why":"The same underworld, and the same theme of return from the dead."},{"to":"sisyphus","why":"Another mortal who briefly bends the rules of death — and loses."}]},{"id":"persephone-demeter","title":"Persephone and Demeter","tradition":"Greek myth","themes":["loss","the seasons","mother and daughter"],"star":{"x":0.8,"y":0.2,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Homeric Hymn to Demeter","author":"Anonymous (Homeric Hymns)","locus":"Hymn II","edition":"trans. Hugh G. Evelyn-White, 1914 (Loeb; public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"The earth gaped wide, and the lord of the dead rose up and seized her, and bore her away weeping in his golden car.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after the Homeric Hymn to Demeter"},"summary":"Hades carries off Persephone to be queen of the underworld. Her mother Demeter, goddess of the harvest, searches the earth in grief and lets all growth fail, threatening famine. Zeus brokers a return — but because Persephone has eaten pomegranate seeds in the underworld, she must spend part of each year below. Her descent and return become the turning of the seasons.","context":"The Hymn is our oldest full account, and it doubles as a charter for the Eleusinian Mysteries, the most important secret cult of ancient Greece. The myth explains winter and spring, but it is also a profound study of a mother's grief and a daughter's passage into a new life. The pomegranate seed — a small act with permanent consequences — is its quiet engine.","characters":[{"name":"Persephone","note":"Daughter of Demeter; abducted maiden who becomes dread queen of the dead, dividing her year between two worlds."},{"name":"Demeter","note":"Goddess of grain and harvest, whose mourning halts all growth on earth."},{"name":"Hades","note":"Lord of the underworld, who seizes Persephone with Zeus's quiet consent."}],"reception":"The Eleusinian Mysteries built rites of death and rebirth around this story for nearly two thousand years. It underlies countless seasonal and fertility myths and has become central to feminist and psychological readings of separation, marriage, and the descent into adulthood. The pomegranate is still its instantly legible symbol.","connections":[{"to":"orpheus-eurydice","why":"The same underworld and rulers; another myth of return from death."},{"to":"pandora","why":"Like the seed, a single irreversible act that reshapes the human world."}]},{"id":"prometheus","title":"Prometheus and the Theft of Fire","tradition":"Greek myth","themes":["defiance","the gift of knowledge","endless punishment"],"star":{"x":0.12,"y":0.52,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Theogony / Works and Days","author":"Hesiod","locus":"Theogony 507–616","edition":"trans. Hugh G. Evelyn-White, 1914 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"He hid the bright gleam of fire in a hollow fennel-stalk and carried it down to men, and Zeus saw, and his heart was filled with anger.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Hesiod, Theogony"},"summary":"The Titan Prometheus champions humankind: he tricks Zeus over the division of sacrifice, then steals fire and gives it to mortals against the god's will. Zeus answers twice — with the punishment of Prometheus, chained to a rock where an eagle devours his ever-renewing liver, and with the making of Pandora, the first woman, sent as a calamity to men.","context":"Hesiod tells the story to explain both human civilization and human suffering: fire is the root of the arts, but it comes bound to divine resentment. Aeschylus later made Prometheus a tragic hero of defiance in Prometheus Bound. The Titan's name means 'forethought,' against his brother Epimetheus, 'afterthought' — the pair embodies a whole theory of human action.","characters":[{"name":"Prometheus","note":"The Titan of forethought, benefactor and trickster, who suffers eternally for siding with mortals."},{"name":"Zeus","note":"King of the gods, whose authority Prometheus repeatedly outwits, and who exacts a limitless punishment."},{"name":"Epimetheus","note":"Prometheus's brother, 'afterthought,' who accepts Pandora despite the warning."}],"reception":"Prometheus became the Romantic emblem of rebellion and creative defiance — Shelley's Prometheus Unbound, and the subtitle of Mary Shelley's Frankenstein, 'The Modern Prometheus.' He stands behind every modern story of stolen knowledge and its price, from nuclear physics to artificial intelligence. The image of the renewing liver gave antiquity its sharpest picture of unending torment.","connections":[{"to":"pandora","why":"Zeus's direct answer to the theft of fire — the two myths are one continuous story in Hesiod."},{"to":"sisyphus","why":"Another figure defined by an eternal, divinely imposed punishment."}]},{"id":"pandora","title":"Pandora's Jar","tradition":"Greek myth","themes":["curiosity","the origin of suffering","hope"],"star":{"x":0.28,"y":0.62,"mag":2},"source":{"work":"Works and Days","author":"Hesiod","locus":"lines 60–105","edition":"trans. Hugh G. Evelyn-White, 1914 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"She lifted the great lid of the jar and scattered its griefs among men; only Hope stayed within, beneath the rim.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Hesiod, Works and Days"},"summary":"As punishment for Prometheus's theft of fire, the gods fashion Pandora, the first woman, each lending her a gift, and send her to humankind. She carries a sealed jar; when it is opened, every hardship and disease escapes into the world. Only Hope remains, caught beneath the lid — a detail that has puzzled readers ever since.","context":"Hesiod's Works and Days uses the myth to explain why human life is full of toil, in a poem otherwise devoted to honest labor and farming. The famous 'box' is a mistranslation — it was a pithos, a large storage jar. What it means that Hope alone stays behind — a comfort kept safe, or a comfort withheld — is left deliberately, productively unresolved.","characters":[{"name":"Pandora","note":"'All-gifted,' the first woman, made by the gods as a beautiful calamity. She opens the jar."},{"name":"Hephaestus","note":"The smith-god who shapes her from earth at Zeus's command."},{"name":"Hope (Elpis)","note":"The one thing that remains inside — the myth's enduring riddle."}],"reception":"'Pandora's box' is now a byword for an irreversible release of troubles, even though the container was a jar. The story has shaped Western ideas about curiosity, blame, and the figure of the first woman, often in close parallel with Eve. Debates over whether Hope is blessing or curse run from antiquity to Nietzsche.","connections":[{"to":"prometheus","why":"Pandora is Zeus's retaliation for the theft of fire — the second half of one story."},{"to":"persephone-demeter","why":"Another myth where a single irreversible act reorders the human condition."}]},{"id":"sisyphus","title":"Sisyphus and the Stone","tradition":"Greek myth","themes":["futility","cunning","defiance of death"],"star":{"x":0.46,"y":0.7,"mag":2},"source":{"work":"Odyssey","author":"Homer","locus":"Book XI (the Underworld)","edition":"trans. Samuel Butler, 1900 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"I saw him straining to push a great stone up a hill; and each time, near the top, its own weight bore it thundering down again.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Homer, Odyssey XI"},"summary":"Sisyphus, a cunning king who twice cheated death — once chaining Thanatos, once tricking his way back from the underworld — is condemned to roll a boulder up a hill forever. Each time he nears the summit, the stone rolls back down, and he must begin again, eternally.","context":"Odysseus glimpses him among the punished dead in the Odyssey's underworld book, alongside Tantalus. Sisyphus's crime was hubris: he thought his wits could outlast the gods and death itself. The image distilled, for antiquity, the idea of labor that can never be completed.","characters":[{"name":"Sisyphus","note":"Founder-king of Corinth, famed for cunning; the cleverest man punished with the most pointless task."},{"name":"Thanatos","note":"Death personified, whom Sisyphus once bound in chains, halting mortality itself."},{"name":"Persephone","note":"Queen of the dead, whom he tricked into letting him return to the living — briefly."}],"reception":"Albert Camus made Sisyphus the central figure of his essay on the absurd, ending with the startling claim that we must imagine him happy. The phrase 'Sisyphean task' is everyday language for endless, fruitless effort. The boulder has become a near-universal symbol of meaningless labor — and, after Camus, of meaning chosen in spite of it.","connections":[{"to":"prometheus","why":"The other great image of eternal, divinely imposed punishment."},{"to":"orpheus-eurydice","why":"Another mortal who briefly outwits death before losing the bargain."}]},{"id":"arachne","title":"Arachne the Weaver","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["pride","art and the gods","transformation"],"star":{"x":0.62,"y":0.6,"mag":2},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book VI, lines 1–145","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"Live on, then — but hang, and keep on weaving; and the touch of the goddess shrank her to a spider.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses VI"},"summary":"The mortal weaver Arachne boasts that her skill rivals Minerva's and refuses to credit the goddess. They hold a contest. Minerva weaves the gods in glory; Arachne weaves the gods' crimes and seductions — flawlessly. Enraged less by losing than by the truth of the work, Minerva strikes her, and as Arachne tries to hang herself the goddess transforms her into a spider, weaving forever.","context":"Ovid opens his sixth book with a story about art that judges its makers. Arachne's tapestry is, pointedly, a catalogue of divine misconduct — the very kind of story Ovid himself is telling — so the myth quietly asks whether the artist who exposes power can survive it. The detail that her weaving was technically perfect makes the punishment about power, not merit.","characters":[{"name":"Arachne","note":"A Lydian woman of humble birth and extraordinary skill at the loom, undone by refusing the gods their due."},{"name":"Minerva","note":"Roman Athena, goddess of wisdom and crafts, patroness of weaving — and a touchy judge."}],"reception":"Velázquez's painting Las Hilanderas sets the contest among ordinary spinners, raising the same question about labor and art. 'Arachnid' and 'arachnophobia' carry her name into science. The story endures as a parable about speaking truth to power through art — and the danger of doing it too well.","connections":[{"to":"apollo-daphne","why":"Another Ovidian transformation that punishes a mortal caught in a god's orbit."},{"to":"icarus-daedalus","why":"Skill and pride brought low — the craftsman's recurring danger."}]},{"id":"the-sirens","title":"Odysseus and the Sirens","tradition":"Greek myth","themes":["temptation","knowledge","self-binding"],"star":{"x":0.78,"y":0.52,"mag":2},"source":{"work":"Odyssey","author":"Homer","locus":"Book XII, lines 154–200","edition":"trans. Samuel Butler, 1900 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"Come here, renowned Odysseus, and listen to our song; no sailor passes without hearing the sweet music of our voices.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Homer, Odyssey XII"},"summary":"Warned by Circe, Odysseus stops his crew's ears with wax so they cannot hear the Sirens, whose song lures sailors to their deaths. He alone wishes to hear it, so he has himself lashed to the mast, ordering the men not to release him no matter how he pleads. He hears the song, struggles, and survives — the one man to hear the Sirens and live.","context":"The episode comes amid the Odyssey's catalogue of perils between Circe's island and home. What the Sirens offer is not pleasure but knowledge — they promise to sing all that happened at Troy. Odysseus's solution, binding himself in advance against his own future desire, has fascinated philosophers as the original image of committing to a plan while distrusting your later self.","characters":[{"name":"Odysseus","note":"The hero of the Odyssey, defined by cunning. Here his curiosity is real but pre-managed."},{"name":"The Sirens","note":"Singers whose voices kill; in Homer they tempt with knowledge, not beauty alone."},{"name":"Circe","note":"The enchantress whose advice makes survival possible."}],"reception":"'Self-binding' is now a standard concept in economics and decision theory, named for this scene; Jon Elster titled a book Ulysses and the Sirens. Kafka inverted it in a parable where the Sirens stay silent. Their image — part-bird in antiquity, later mermaid-like — runs through art, opera, and the very word for a warning alarm.","connections":[{"to":"orpheus-eurydice","why":"Music as a force with power over life and death."},{"to":"icarus-daedalus","why":"Both turn on heeding, or ignoring, a warning given in advance."}]},{"id":"phaethon","title":"Phaethon and the Chariot of the Sun","tradition":"Greek myth, Roman source","themes":["youth","overreach","a father's promise"],"star":{"x":0.4,"y":0.42,"mag":1},"source":{"work":"Metamorphoses","author":"Ovid","locus":"Book II, lines 1–328","edition":"trans. Brookes More, 1922 (public domain)."},"passage":{"kind":"rendering","text":"The horses felt the lighter hand and bolted, and the boy could neither name them nor hold the reins — and the world below began to burn.","attribution":"Editor's rendering after Ovid, Metamorphoses II"},"summary":"To prove his divine parentage, the boy Phaethon asks his father, the sun-god, for a single day driving the sun's chariot across the sky. Bound by an oath, the god reluctantly agrees. Phaethon cannot control the immortal horses; the chariot careers wild, scorching the earth, until Zeus strikes him down with a thunderbolt to save the world. He falls flaming into a river.","context":"Ovid gives Phaethon a sweeping, cinematic treatment at the start of his second book — the sky catching fire, rivers drying, the constellations terrified. It is the great cautionary tale of a child who demands the privileges of a parent's power without the capacity to wield it, and of a father whose love, expressed as an unbreakable promise, destroys his son.","characters":[{"name":"Phaethon","note":"Son of the sun-god, who demands proof of his lineage and pays with his life."},{"name":"Helios / Phoebus","note":"The sun-god, his father, trapped by his own oath into granting a fatal wish."},{"name":"Zeus","note":"Who ends the catastrophe with a thunderbolt to spare the earth."}],"reception":"Phaethon became the byword for ruinous ambition and was a favorite of Baroque ceiling painters depicting the fiery fall. His sisters, the Heliades, weeping at his death, were turned into poplars dripping amber — a myth explaining the origin of that stone. The car name 'Phaeton' descends, with some irony, from this story of a vehicle out of control.","connections":[{"to":"icarus-daedalus","why":"Two boys destroyed by climbing too near the sun — antiquity's twin parables of overreach."},{"to":"apollo-daphne","why":"The same sun-god, here as a grieving father bound by his word."}]}]};
